%U A394629 172,150,168,149,136,271,261,513,502,481,439,463,447,808,705,738,778
%N A394629 Number of pairs of primes (p, q) such that n! = q^2 - p^2.
%C A394629 See A394631 for the smallest p and A394632 for the corresponding q.
%C A394629 We have n! = q^2 - p^2 = (q - p)*(q + p) so that q, p = |n!/d +- d|/2 for some divisor d of n!. The number of these divisors grows quite fast (e.g., 10^8 for n=40), see A027423 and A138196 for the number of decompositions as difference of squares.
%C A394629 It appears that the growth of these numbers is such that it compensates for the decreasing density of primes, leading to a growing number of solutions as n grows.
%C A394629 It also appears that in general there are less solutions for even n than for odd n. We have a(n) < a(n-1) for n = 9, 16, 18, 20, 24, 26, 34, 35, 36, 38, 40, 42, 44, 46, 48, 49, 51, 52, 55, 57, 58, 60, ...
%C A394629 There are at most 2^(primepi(n)) divisors d such that gcd(n!/d, d) = 2. To ensure no double counting let 2^v | d where v + 1 is the 2-adic valuation of n!. - _David A. Corneth_, Apr 09 2026
%C A394629 Otherwise said, we have q, p = |f/d +- d| where f = n!/4 and d has either all or none of the prime factors of f, for any given prime. - _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 11 2026
%H A394629 Dony, <a href="https://qr.ae/pFT5R9">Re: Est-il vrai que pour tout entier n >= 4 il existe au moins une paire de nombres premiers p < q tels que n! = q^2 - p^2?</a>, fr.Quora.com, March 2026.
%e A394629 For n < 4 there can't be any such p, q because 3^2 - 2^2 = 5 and 5^2 - 3^2 = 16 is already larger than 3! = 6, so a(n) = 0.
%e A394629 For n = 4 we have 7^2 - 5^2 = 49 - 25 = 24 = 4!, so (p, q) = (5, 7) is the only solution, so a(4) = 1.
%e A394629 For n = 5 we have 5! = 120 = 13^2 - 7^2 = 17^2 - 13^2 = 31^2 - 29^2, so we have a(5) = 3 solutions (7, 13), (13, 17) and (29, 31).
%o A394629 (PARI) apply( {A394629(n)=my(f=if(n>3, factor(n=n!\4)[2..-1,]~), d); sum(m=0, 2^#f-1, d=if(m,factorback(vecextract(f,m)~),1); ispseudoprime(abs(n\d-d))&& ispseudoprime(n\d+d))}, [0..30])
%o A394629 (PARI) a(n)=if(n<4,return(0));my(N=n!);sumdiv(vecprod(primes([3,n])),d,my(U=2*gcd(d^n,N));ispseudoprime(abs(N/U-U)/2)&&ispseudoprime((N/U+U)/2)); \\ _Daniel Suteu_, Apr 10 2026
%o A394629 (SageMath) # see Dony link.
%Y A394629 Cf. A027423 (number of divisors of n!), A394630 - A394633 (smallest p and q and their indices within the primes).
%Y A394629 Cf. A138196 (similar with p, q not necessarily prime).
%Y A394629 Cf. A000720, A001221.
